  <data key="d14">ann.concept-precepts-of-temperance-parts-forbids-opposed-vice-of-concept-anger-vice-st-ii-ii-q170-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q170.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ition of the effects of the vices opposed to the parts of temperance . Thus the effect of anger , which is opposed to meekness, is sometimes that a man goes on to commit murder (and this is forbidden in the Decalogue ), and sometimes that he refuses due honor to his parents,</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d19">precept</data>
